2021 Narrative: -	UNMAS Iraq implemented a study on Socio-Economic Empowerment of Women through Mine Action in Ninewa Governorate. The result of this assessment demonstrates that there was an impact of individual and community transformation in the mine action survey and clearance activities from 2017 to 2020. Women of mine action made evident development in their skills, improved their agency, and felt empowered within their families and communities. In the workplace, they demonstrated their capacity to the majority of male colleagues and supervisors. At a personal level, their self-perceptions portray life changing levels of socio-economic-personal empowerment for many of them, and career ambitions by most. Community return and socio-economic recovery are interrelated, through the capacity of local communities to create job opportunities.

2021 Narrative:
-	An internal stakeholder mapping document was developed by the UNMAS Iraq Technical Support team to create an overview and highlight the different responsibilities of each mine action stakeholder. The identified stakeholder map was an opportunity to develop specific advocacy points to support  the Directorate of Mine action in their interactions with other line ministries within the Government of Iraq.
-	The UNMAS Iraq TS team, consisting of technical experts, advisors and liaison officers, had continued to support mine action actors, with a specific focus on the National Mine Action Standards where four  strategic objectives were drafted. 
-	A Basic Humanitarian Mine Action Management training was conducted in Anbar governorate for the JCMC office and 17 GoI departments. 
-	UNMAS Iraq provided 23 trainings  for 296 (231 male, 64 female) Ministry of Interior police officers; trainings varied among Explosive Ordnance Disposal (EOD), Explosive Hazard First Responder, and Device Scene Incident Management (DSIM) courses.

Plan name: United Nations Sustainable Development Cooperation Framework 2023 - 2026
Outcome: Planet1: Improved gender inclusive environmental management and governance
Output: Planet1.2: Tools and processes for climate change actions and resilience are strengthened
Sub-Output: The Paris Agreement in Action: Upscaling Forest and Landscape Restoration to Achieve Nationally Determined Contributions
Description:
As recognized in the Paris Agreement, forest-based options are key to achieve countries’ Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) through joint mitigation and adaptation approaches (REDD+) providing both carbon and non-carbon-benefits. The effective implementation of the Bonn Challenge, through several existing Forest and Landscape Restoration (FLR) regional initiatives, represents an opportunity to scale up restoration impacts, thus con-tributing to achieving Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs). 
I) Three regions with diverse landscapes and high potential for increasing both forest carbon stocks and the provision of non-carbon benefits through large scale FLR programmes are targeted: 
(i)	Pacific Islands with two active members of the Asia-Pacific Forestry Com-mission (APFC) already working with FAO and its FLRM (Philippines + Fiji)
(ii)	Great Green Wall for the Sahara and the Sahel Initiative (GGWSSI) with two targeted partners strongly involved in the FAO-led Action Against Desertification project (Ethiopia + Niger) 
(iii)	Mediterranean region with two key members of the Committee on Mediter-ranean Forestry Questions-Silva Mediterranea involved in Forest and Landscape Restoration efforts (Lebanon + Morocco).
Agencies: Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations
Contributing partners: Germany Federal Ministry for the Environment, Nature Conservation, Building and Nuclear Safety/International Climate Initiative
Implementation partners: Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations
SDG Targets: 15.a Mobilize and significantly increase financial resources from all sources to conserve and sustainable use biodiversity and ecosystems.

Sustaining peace marker narrative: The objective of the project is Forest and Landscape restoration (FLR). The expected outcome of the project is improved resilience, productivity and socio-economic value from restored forests and landscapes benefiting human well-being, local livelihoods and the environment. It aims to seek a balance be-tween restoring ecosystem services (e.g. biodiversity, soil and water conserva-tion) and productive functions of land for agriculture and related uses that provide food, energy and other products and services for sustainable liveli-hoods.
